# .dockerignore — Module 06 (the .dockerignore deep-dive)
#
# ── WHAT IS THE BUILD CONTEXT? ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# When you run `docker build .`, Docker:
#   1. Bundles everything in the current directory (.) into a tar archive.
#   2. Sends that archive (the "build context") to the Docker daemon over a
#      Unix socket (or TCP in remote builds).
#   3. The daemon unpacks the archive and makes it available to Dockerfile
#      COPY/ADD instructions.
#
# This bundling happens BEFORE Docker even reads the Dockerfile.
# Every file and directory in the context is transferred regardless of whether
# any instruction ever references it. Large contexts = slow every single build.
#
# .dockerignore tells Docker what to EXCLUDE from the bundle before it is sent.
# Excluded files never reach the daemon, so they cannot be COPYed, cannot
# bloat the image, and cannot appear in build logs or layer caches.
#
# ── SYNTAX ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Same pattern syntax as .gitignore:
#   *          matches any string (except path separators)
#   **         matches any path (including separators)
#   ?          matches any single character
#   !pattern   negates (re-includes) a previously excluded match
#   # comment  lines starting with # are comments

# ── secrets.env ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Exclude the fake secrets file (and any real .env files in the project).
#
# WHY: A .env file typically contains database passwords, API keys, and other
# credentials used in local development. If this file reaches the Docker daemon:
#   - A `COPY . .` instruction bakes it into the image layer — readable by
#     anyone who pulls or runs the image.
#   - Even without COPY, the file was transmitted and may appear in build logs
#     or be visible in intermediate layer caches.
#   - An image pushed to a registry leaks those credentials to everyone who
#     has pull access.
# RULE: Never bake secrets into an image. Pass them at runtime:
#   docker run --env-file secrets.env myimage:1.0.0
#   or use a secrets manager (AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault, Docker secrets).
secrets.env
*.env
.env

# ── big-data/ ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Exclude the large data directory.
#
# WHY: The build context is sent to the Docker daemon as a tar archive over a
# socket. Large files in the context cause:
#   - Slow build startup: every `docker build` transfers those files first,
#     even before reading the Dockerfile, even when all layers are cached.
#   - Bloated images if COPY . . is used: a Python web server does not need
#     gigabytes of training data baked into its image — it should fetch data
#     from object storage (S3, GCS) at runtime.
#   - Wasted CI/CD bandwidth: remote runners (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI)
#     transmit the context over the network — GB-scale contexts waste minutes.
# RULE: Large data files belong in cloud object storage or a volume, not in
# the image. Exclude any data directory here.
big-data/

# ── __pycache__ ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Exclude Python bytecode cache directories.
#
# WHY: Python compiles .py files to .pyc bytecode and caches them in
# __pycache__/ directories. These files are:
#   - Platform-specific: .pyc compiled on macOS will not work on Linux inside
#     the container — Python regenerates them automatically on first import anyway.
#   - Wasteful: including them inflates the build context and the image for zero
#     benefit, since they are recreated at runtime.
#   - Cluttering: if you bind-mount source code, __pycache__ files created by
#     the container appear on your host filesystem, owned by the container user.
# We also set PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE=1 in the Dockerfile so Python does not
# generate them at all inside the container.
__pycache__/
*.pyc
*.pyo
*.pyd

# ── .git ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Exclude the Git repository metadata directory.
#
# WHY: .git contains the complete commit history of your repository — every
# file you have ever committed, every commit message, every branch. Including it:
#   - Inflates the build context significantly (can be hundreds of MB for
#     long-lived repos or those with large binary history).
#   - Exposes your complete development history to anyone who inspects the image
#     or extracts its layers with `docker save`.
#   - Is never needed at runtime — the running container has no use for git history.
.git/
.gitignore
.gitattributes

# ── Developer documentation ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Exclude notes and README files.
#
# WHY: These files are valuable to developers reading the source code but are
# irrelevant to the running container. Including them adds unnecessary bytes to
# the build context and, if COPYed, to the image layer.
notes.md
README.md
*.md

# ── Editor / IDE configuration ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Exclude IDE and editor config directories.
#
# WHY: These files contain personal editor preferences, workspace settings, and
# sometimes credentials (e.g. `.idea/` may contain database connection strings).
# They are never needed inside a container.
.vscode/
.idea/
*.swp
*.swo

# ── OS artifacts ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# macOS and Windows create these files automatically in every directory.
# They are never useful inside a container.
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
desktop.ini

# ── Python virtual environment ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# If a developer has a local venv, exclude it — it is OS-specific and large.
#
# WHY: A virtual environment created on macOS or Windows contains OS-specific
# compiled binaries that will not work on Linux inside the container. The
# Dockerfile installs the correct Linux versions via pip. A local venv in the
# build context would just add hundreds of MB to the transfer for nothing.
.venv/
venv/
env/
